[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] In computing, an **abstraction layer** or **abstraction level** is a way of hiding the working details of a subsystem.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] Examples of software models that use layers of abstraction include the OSI model for network protocols, OpenGL, and other graphics libraries, which allow the separation of concerns to facilitate interoperability and platform independence.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] In computer science, an abstraction layer is a generalization of a conceptual model or algorithm, away from any specific implementation.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] These generalizations arise from broad similarities that are best encapsulated by models that express similarities present in various specific implementations.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] The simplification provided by a good abstraction layer allows for easy reuse by distilling a useful concept or design pattern so that situations, where it may be accurately applied, can be quickly recognized.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] Just composing lower-level elements into a construct doesn't count as an abstraction layer unless it shields users from its underlying complexity.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] A layer is considered to be on top of another if it depends on it.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] Every layer can exist without the layers above it, and requires the layers below it to function.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] Frequently, abstraction layers can be composed into a hierarchy of abstraction levels.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] The OSI model comprises seven abstraction layers.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] Each layer of the model encapsulates and addresses a different part of the needs of digital communications, thereby reducing the complexity of the associated engineering solutions.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] A famous aphorism of David Wheeler is, "All problems in computer science can be solved by another level of indirection." This is often deliberately misquoted with "abstraction" substituted for "indirection." It is also sometimes misattributed to Butler Lampson.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] Programmable logic is often considered part of the hardware, while the logical definitions are also sometimes seen as part of a device's software or firmware.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] Firmware may include only low-level software, but can also include all software, including an operating system and applications.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] The software layers can be further divided into hardware abstraction layers, physical and logical device drivers, repositories such as filesystems, operating system kernels, middleware, applications, and others.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] A distinction can also be made between low-level programming languages like VHDL, machine language, assembly language and a compiled language, interpreter, or script language.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] In the Unix operating system, most types of input and output operations are considered to be streams of bytes read from a device or written to a device.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] This stream of bytes model is used for file I/O, socket I/O, and terminal I/O in order to provide device independence.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] In order to read and write to a device at the application level, the program calls a function to open the device, which may be a real device, such as a terminal or a virtual device, such as a network port or a file in a file system.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] The device's physical characteristics are mediated by the operating system, which in turn presents an abstract interface that allows the programmer to read and write bytes from/to the device.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] The operating system then performs the actual transformation needed to read and write the stream of bytes to the device.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] Most graphics libraries, such as OpenGL, provide an abstract graphical device model as an interface.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/abstraction-layer] The library is responsible for translating the commands provided by the programmer into the specific device commands needed to draw the graphical elements and objects.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] The **facade pattern** (also spelled *façade*) is a software design pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] Analogous to a façade in architecture, it is an object that serves as a front-facing interface masking more complex underlying or structural code.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] Developers often use the facade design pattern when a system is very complex or difficult to understand because the system has many interdependent classes or because its source code is unavailable.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] This pattern hides the complexities of the larger system and provides a simpler interface to the client.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] It typically involves a single wrapper class that contains a set of members required by the client.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] These members access the system on behalf of the facade client and hide the implementation details.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] The Facade design pattern is one of the twenty-three well-known *GoF design patterns* that describe how to solve recurring design problems to design flexible and reusable object-oriented software, that is, objects that are easier to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] What problems can the Facade design pattern solve?
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] Clients that access a complex subsystem directly refer to (depend on) many different objects having different interfaces (tight coupling), which makes the clients hard to implement, change, test, and reuse.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] What solution does the Facade design pattern describe?
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] This enables to work through a `Facade` object to minimize the dependencies on a subsystem.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] See also the UML class and sequence diagram below.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] A Facade is used when an easier or simpler interface to an underlying object is desired.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] Alternatively, an adapter can be used when the wrapper must respect a particular interface and must support polymorphic behavior.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] A decorator makes it possible to add or alter behavior of an interface at run-time.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] A good example of where a facade is used is in register indexed values like Modbus, I2C or Special function register.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] In this UML class diagram, the `Client` class doesn't access the subsystem classes directly.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] Instead, the `Client` works through a `Facade` class that implements a simple interface in terms of (by delegating to) the subsystem classes (`Class1`, `Class2`, and `Class3`).
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] The `Client` depends only on the simple `Facade` interface and is independent of the complex subsystem.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] The sequence diagram shows the run-time interactions: The `Client` object works through a `Facade` object that delegates the request to the `Class1`, `Class2`, and `Class3` instances that perform the request.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] The facade class abstracts Packages 1, 2, and 3 from the rest of the application.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/facade-pattern] The objects are using the facade pattern to access resources from the packages.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] A **Java logging framework** is a computer data logging package for the Java platform.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] This article covers general purpose logging frameworks.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Logging refers to the recording of activity by an application and is a common issue for development teams.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Logging frameworks ease and standardize the process of logging for the Java platform.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] In particular they provide flexibility by avoiding explicit output to the console (see Appender below).
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Where logs are written becomes independent of the code and can be customized at runtime.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Unfortunately the JDK did not include logging in its original release so by the time the Java Logging API was added several other logging frameworks had become widely used – in particular Apache Commons Logging (also known as Java Commons Logging or JCL) and Log4j.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] This led to problems when integrating different third-party libraries (JARs) each using different logging frameworks.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Pluggable logging frameworks (wrappers) were developed to solve this problem.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Logging is typically broken into three major pieces: the Logger, the Formatter and the Appender (or Handler).
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Simpler logging frameworks, like |Java Logging Framework by the Object Guy, combine the logger and the appender.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] This simplifies default operation, but it is less configurable, especially if the project is moved across environments.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] A Logger is an object that allows the application to log without regard to where the output is sent/stored.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The application logs a message by passing an object or an object and an exception with an optional severity level to the logger object under a given name/identifier.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The name is usually structured hierarchically, with periods (.) separating the levels.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] A common scheme is to use the name of the class or package that is doing the logging.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Both Log4j and the Java logging API support defining handlers higher up the hierarchy.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] For example, the logger might be named "`com.sun.some.UsefulClass`".
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] As long as there is a handler defined somewhere in this stack, logging may occur.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] For example a message logged to the `com.sun.some.UsefulClass` logger, may get written by the `com.sun` handler.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Typically there is a global handler that receives and processes messages generated by any logger.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The message is logged at a certain level.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The logging framework maintains the current logging level for each logger.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The logging level can be set more or less restrictive.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] For example, if the logging level is set to "WARNING", then all messages of that level or higher are logged: ERROR and FATAL.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Severity levels can be assigned to both loggers and appenders.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Both must be enabled for a given severity level for output to be generated.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] So a logger enabled for debug output will not generate output if the handler that gets the message is not also enabled for debug.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Filters cause a log event to be ignored or logged.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The most commonly used filter is the logging level documented in the previous section.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Logging frameworks such as Log4j 2 and SLF4J also provide Markers, which when attached to a log event can also be used for filtering.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Filters can also be used to accept or deny log events based on exceptions being thrown, data within the log message, data in a ThreadLocal that is exposed through the logging API, or a variety of other methods.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] A Formatter is an object that formats a given object.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Mostly this consists of taking the binary object and converting it to a string representation.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Each framework defines a default output format that can be overridden if desired.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Appenders listen for messages at or above a specified minimum severity level.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The Appender takes the message it is passed and posts it appropriately.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] JCL and Log4j are very common simply because they have been around for so long and were the only choices for a long time.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The flexibility of slf4j (using Logback underneath) has made it a popular choice.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] SLF4J is a set of logging wrappers (or shims) that allow it to imitate any of the other frameworks.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Thus multiple third-party libraries can be incorporated into an application, regardless of the logging framework each has chosen to use.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] However all logging output is generated in a standard way, typically via Logback.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Log4j 2 provides both an API and an implementation.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The API can be routed to other logging implementations equivalent to how SLF4J works.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Unlike SLF4J, the Log4j 2 API logs Message objects instead of Strings for extra flexibility and also supports Java Lambda expressions.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] JCL isn't really a logging framework, but a wrapper for one.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] As such, it requires a logging framework underneath it, although it can default to using its own `SimpleLog` logger.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] JCL, SLF4J and the Log4j 2 API are useful when developing reusable libraries which need to write to whichever underlying logging system is being used by the application.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] This also provides flexibility in heterogeneous environments where the logging framework is likely to change, although in most cases, once a logging framework has been chosen, there is little need to change it over the life of the project.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] SLF4J and Log4j 2 benefit from being newer and build on the lessons learned from older frameworks.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Moreover JCL has known problems with class-loaders when determining what logging library it should wrap which has now replaced JCL.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The Java Logging API is provided with Java.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Although the API is technically separate from the default implementation provided with Java, replacing it with an alternate implementation can be challenging so many developers confuse this implementation with the Java Logging API.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] Configuration is by external files only which is not easily changed on the fly (other frameworks support programmatic configuration).
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-logging-framework] The default implementation only provides a few Handlers and Formatters which means most users will have to write their own.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
