[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Java servlet technology provides Web developers with a simple, consistent mechanism for extending the functionality of a Web server and for accessing existing business systems.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Servlets are server-side Java EE components that generate responses to requests from clients.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Most of the time, this means generating HTML pages in response to HTTP requests, although there are a number of other standard servlet classes available, for example for WebSocket communication.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] Typical implementations of these APIs on Application Servers or Servlet Containers use a standard servlet for handling all interactions with the HTTP requests and responses that delegate to the web service methods for the actual business logic.
[src:slf4j-logging-java/java-programming-language] JavaServer Pages (JSP) are server-side Java EE components that generate responses, typically HTML pages, to HTTP requests from clients.
